T1  - BUSINESS CYCLES, TREND ELIMINATION, AND THE HP FILTER
AU  - Phillips, Peter C. B.
AU  - Jin, Sainan
Y1  - 2021/05/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12494
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 469
EP  - 520
VL  - 62
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12494
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Trend elimination and business cycle estimation are analyzed by finite sample and asymptotic methods. An overview history is provided, operator theory is developed, limit theory as the sample size is derived, and filtered series properties are studied relative to smoothing parameter () behavior. Simulations reveal that limit theory with delivers excellent approximations to the HP filter for common sample sizes but fails to remove stochastic trends, contrary to standard thinking in macroeconomics and thereby explaining ?spurious cycle? effects of the HP filter. The findings are related to the long run effects of the global financial crisis.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - BOOSTING: WHY YOU CAN USE THE HP FILTER
AU  - Phillips, Peter C. B.
AU  - Shi, Zhentao
Y1  - 2021/05/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12495
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 521
EP  - 570
VL  - 62
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12495
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We propose a procedure of iterating the HP filter to produce a smarter smoothing device, called the boosted HP (bHP) filter, based on L2-boosting in machine learning. Limit theory shows that the bHP filter asymptotically recovers trend mechanisms that involve integrated processes, deterministic drifts, and structural breaks, covering the most common trends that appear in current modeling methodology. A stopping criterion automates the algorithm, giving a data-determined method for data-rich environments. The methodology is illustrated in simulations and with three real data examples that highlight the differences between simple HP filtering, the bHP filter, and an alternative autoregressive approach.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - WHAT IS SOCIALISM TODAY? CONCEPTIONS OF A COOPERATIVE ECONOMY
AU  - Roemer, John E.
Y1  - 2021/05/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12498
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 571
EP  - 598
VL  - 62
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12498
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Socialism is back on the political agenda in the United States. I propose several variants of socialism, characterized by different kinds of property relation in the ownership of firms. In addition to property relations, a conception of socialism should include a specification of the cooperative ethos, in place of the individualistic ethos of capitalist society. Individualistic economic agents will optimize in the manner of John Nash, whereas cooperative ones do so in the manner of Immanuel Kant. I argue that Kantian optimization decentralizes resource allocation in ways that separate issues of equity (income distribution) from efficiency. I offer tentative thoughts concerning how we should conceive of socialism today.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - HOMEOWNERSHIP AND HOUSING TRANSITIONS: EXPLAINING THE DEMOGRAPHIC COMPOSITION
AU  - Ma, Eunseong
AU  - Zubairy, Sarah
Y1  - 2021/05/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12493
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 599
EP  - 638
VL  - 62
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12493
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We document the evolution of homeownership rate across various age groups for the period 1995?2015. We find that variations in the homeownership rates are relatively large for the young, which is mostly driven by renter-to-owner transitions. In order to explain these empirical facts, we consider a life-cycle model featuring housing tenure decisions. Housing is modeled as an indivisible and lumpy investment subject to both loan-to-value (LTV) and debt-to-income (DTI) credit constraints and transaction fees. Our analysis suggests that variations in the DTI limit play a crucial role in accounting for the uneven behavior across age groups.
ER  - 

